faq:
  - q: "What is a mock interview?"
    a: "A mock interview is a simulated job interview conducted with a coach or practice partner to prepare for real interviews. A high-quality mock interview mirrors the actual format — behavioral, technical, or case-based — at the target level and provides specific, calibrated feedback on what to improve. The goal is to experience the pressure of a real interview before the stakes are real."
  - q: "How many mock interviews do I need to prepare?"
    a: "Most candidates need 3–5 mock interviews to move from hesitant to confident. The first session identifies the most critical gaps. Sessions 2 and 3 address those gaps and build consistency. Sessions 4 and 5 simulate full-length, pressure interviews at pace. The right number depends on how far your current answers are from the target level — some candidates need more, some fewer."
  - q: "What types of mock interviews does Askia offer?"
    a: "Askia offers behavioral mock interviews (STAR method, competency-based questions), role-specific mock interviews (software engineering, product management, data, finance, executive), and senior leadership simulations (Director, VP, C-suite positioning interviews). Each session is calibrated to the specific company, role level, and interview format the client is targeting."
  - q: "How is Askia's mock interview coaching different from AI mock interview tools?"
    a: "AI mock interview tools give generic feedback based on keyword matching and filler word detection. Askia's coaching gives specific feedback based on what hiring managers at the target company and level are actually evaluating. Steve Ngoumnai reviewed thousands of candidates and made hundreds of hiring decisions — the feedback is calibrated to what moves real decisions, not what sounds good in the abstract."
  - q: "What does feedback from a mock interview look like?"
    a: "Feedback from an Askia mock interview covers: answer structure and specificity, level signal (are you landing at the right seniority?), quantification gaps (where numbers are missing), decision framing (are you showing your reasoning?), and pacing and delivery. You receive specific rewrites for your weakest answers, not just general notes."
